<article>
    <h1>TIPS FOR THROW&#xAD;ING A PARTY</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201213/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-13"><time>2020-12-13</time></a>
        - <span>SINGAPORE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Cater for less than the num­ber of guests ex­pected. When cater­ing for an event, it is usu­ally safe to or­der for 10 per cent to 15 per cent less than the num­ber of guests at­tend­ing.</p>
    <p>Potluck meals should be care­fully planned. Ask your guests for the type and quan­tity of food that they are con­tribut­ing to the meal.</p>
    <p>When pre­par­ing food for a party, pro­vide just enough. Down­size the por­tion of each dish if you are plan­ning to serve a va­ri­ety of dishes.</p>
    <p>• If you have to pro­vide a large amount of food, por­tion be­fore serv­ing so that left­overs are kept clean for stor­age and fu­ture con­sump­tion.</p>
    <p>Not sure how to es­ti­mate how much food is needed? Try us­ing the free Healthy Chef app by the Health Pro­mo­tion Board. It helps you ad­just recipes based on the num­ber of serv­ings re­quired.</p>
    <p>Keep it neat. En­cour­age your guests not to leave any scraps on their plates. It makes clean­ing eas­ier and min­imises wastage.</p>

